911 Calls Capstone Project¶

For this capstone project we will be analyzing some 911 call data from Kaggle. The data contains the following fields:

  • lat : String variable, Latitude
  • lng: String variable, Longitude
  • desc: String variable, Description of the Emergency Call
  • zip: String variable, Zipcode
  • title: String variable, Title
  • timeStamp: String variable, YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS
  • twp: String variable, Township
  • addr: String variable, Address
  • e: String variable, Dummy variable (always 1)

Just go along with this notebook and try to complete the instructions or answer the questions in bold using your Python and Data Science skills!

Creating new features¶

** In the titles column there are "Reasons/Departments" specified before the title code. These are EMS, Fire, and Traffic. Use .apply() with a custom lambda expression to create a new column called "Reason" that contains this string value.**

For example, if the title column value is EMS: BACK PAINS/INJURY , the Reason column value would be EMS.

df["Reason"]=df["title"].apply(lambda x:x.split(":")[0])

Now that the timestamp column are actually DateTime objects, use .apply() to create 3 new columns called Hour, Month, and Day of Week. You will create these columns based off of the timeStamp column, reference the solutions if you get stuck on this step.

In [41]:
df["Month"]=df["timeStamp"].apply(lambda x:x.month)

df["Day_of_week"]=df["timeStamp"].apply(lambda x:x.dayofweek)
df["Hour"]=df["timeStamp"].apply(lambda x:x.hour)

** Notice how the Day of Week is an integer 0-6. Use the .map() with this dictionary to map the actual string names to the day of the week: **

dmap = {0:'Mon',1:'Tue',2:'Wed',3:'Thu',4:'Fri',5:'Sat',6:'Sun'}

** Now recreate this plot but create 3 separate plots with each plot representing a Reason for the 911 call**

In [102]:
# Group by Date and Reason, then count the number of occurrences
df_grouped = df.groupby(["Date", "Reason"]).size().unstack()

# Plot each reason separately
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 1, figsize=(12, 10), sharex=True)

# Plot for each Reason
for ax, reason in zip(axes, df_grouped.columns):
    df_grouped[reason].plot(ax=ax, legend=True, title=f"{reason} Calls Over Time")
    ax.set_ylabel("Number of Calls")

plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In [115]:
df_grouped =df.groupby(["Date","Reason"]).size().unstack().plot.line()
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()
